  "text": "If the adversary obtains the trained model, including network weights, the number and type of layers, the number of convolutional channels and size of its kernels, this makes his attack a white-box attack by definition. He will approach the AdEx design in a classical way by utilizing the loss function dependent on the trained weights, which are know to him. An interesting effect is presented in Figure 7 when a gray-box attack is performed, which is the weaker attack when everything else but the actual weights are known. In simpler terms, the adversarial examples are created on an independently trained network, but applied to the AE trained network, without transfer of weights. The AE-trained network maintains resilience against AdExs. Note that the proposed defense demands a modification of the white box definition, as the last layer (or layers) needs to be different, depending on where the AE bottleneck is. This promising AE-based defense can be further improved by drawing on our research on channel-robust Stacked Denoising Autoencoder [CITATION_1] .",
